malized": true, "mention": "NR2A NMDAR subunits", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9601641297340393, "span": {"begin": 638, "end": 657}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "spine", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.49054035544395447, "span": {"begin": 667, "end": 672}}, {"id": ["CHEBI:30039"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "C", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.6620962023735046, "span": {"begin": 768, "end": 769}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:7182"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "NR2", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.989296019077301, "span": {"begin": 782, "end": 785}}], "text": "The NMDA receptor activation by glutamate during development increases calcium influx, which acts as a secondary signal. Eventually, immediate early genes (IEG) activation is triggered by transcription factors and the proteins required for synapse formation are produced (reviewed in Ghiani et al., 2007). Glutamate released from entorhinal cortex neurons has been shown to promote synaptogenesis in developing targeted hippocampal neurons (Mattson et al., 1988). Similarly, glutamate has been found to regulate synaptogenesis in the developing visual system of frogs (Cline and Constantine-Paton, 1990).  The ratio of synaptic NR2B over NR2A NMDAR subunits controls spine motility and synaptogenesis, and it has been suggested a structural role for the intracellular C terminus of NR2 in recruiting the signaling and scaffolding molecules necessary for proper synaptogenesis (Gambrill and Barria, 2011).", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 14:27:26 +0000 2026"}